John Edward: Language skills are essential for a citizen of the world
The Scottish primary schools have traditionally been successful in their learning outcomes, and this success has continued in 2018 following strong test scores, reinforced by individual and community success in sport, the arts, music and other community projects.
These schools, with over 30 000 pupils spread across Scotland, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide a high standard of service to their pupils and parents.
Private schools aim to prepare their pupils for their chosen career, for further and higher education, and for world citizenship.
As an educational actor capable of designing and implementing tailored learning content, we have noticed the position of languages as the preferred and desired subject in continuing education institutions.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a person in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you speak to a person in his own language, the message goes to his heart.
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely solely on the English language if we want to build trusting relationships with people in other countries.
The latest results for this year show that languages are at the top of the list in terms of the percentage of students who pass through the private schools.
68% of pupils studying foreign languages achieved the highest A grade.
The data were collected from 74 SCIS schools, and it was found that of the students who received the highest grade, 72% studied Mandarin, 72% studied German, 69% studied French, and 63% studied Spanish.
This shows that the private schools in Scotland support the study of foreign languages as an essential skill that children and young people will no doubt need in the future.
Languages are currently optional subjects, but they are given the same value as natural science subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curriculum of private schools and elsewhere.
The UK Employment Office survey conducted in 2014 found that 17% of the situations where an employer had difficulty finding a suitable employee for the job were explained by a lack of language skills.
The development of language skills is therefore all the more necessary in order to promote the future career development of young people.
The more the potential jobs require language skills, the more essential these skills become in a global world.
Having studied another language, one has a future advantage in this lifelong skill, regardless of the career one has chosen.
The ability to communicate directly with a foreigner automatically puts the person with a language skills ahead of the competition.
A survey by YouGov in 2013 of more than 4,000 British adults found that 75 per cent could not hold a conversation in a foreign language, with French being the only language that was spoken by a double-digit number of 15 per cent.
This is why investing in language learning is important for today's children.
Knowing the languages of developing countries, in particular, gives children a better chance of finding a meaningful career.
Within Scotland, schools differ in the languages they teach.
Many schools focus on traditional languages, while some teach specifically languages that are expected to be important to Britons in 2020, such as Mandarin and Japanese.
Whatever your child's interests, there are always several language options in private schools, taught by specialised teachers.
Private schools in Scotland are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future may bring.
In this era, it is undeniable that in the international business environment, languages will continue to be very important for the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should be seen as 'international communication skills'.
Private schools will continue to provide this freedom of choice, diversity and high standards for young people in Scotland.
I must be fair.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Schools Council, SCIS.
