North Korea will not under any circumstances disarm itself without confidence.
North Korea's foreign minister told the UN on Saturday that continued sanctions were only increasing mistrust of the United States, and under these circumstances, there is no chance that North Korea would unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the UN General Assembly that North Korea has taken "significant acts of goodwill" over the past year, including stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test site and promising not to increase its nuclear weapons or technology.
'However, we have not seen a similar gesture from the United States,' he said.
Without trust in the United States, we cannot be sure of the preservation of national security, so in these circumstances, unilaterally disarming ourselves is not possible.
While Ri repeated the familiar lament that Washington does not accept a phased nuclear disarmament that would reward North Korea for every intermediate step, his statement is nonetheless significant in that it does not completely rule out unilateral disarmament, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to the joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between the sitting US president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on 12 June, in which Kim pledged "the denuclearisation of the Korean Peninsula" and Trump promised to guarantee the security of North Korea.
North Korea has sought to officially end the 1950-1953 Korean War, but the United States has insisted that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also opposed the easing of the tough international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
The US demands nuclear disarmament first and has increased pressure through sanctions to achieve its goals by force, even in opposition to the peace declaration, said Ri.
The idea that sanctions will bring us to our knees is the wish of the indifferent.
But the problem is that continuing to impose sanctions only deepen our mistrust.
Ri did not mention plans to hold the next Kim-Trump summit, which Trump himself emphasized to the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings with South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the last five months, adding: If the disarmament demanding party had been South Korea and not the US, the situation would not have reached this impasse.
Yet Rin's tone was markedly different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that the missile attack on the continental United States was inevitable after "evil President" Trump called Kim "missile man" with a suicidal intent.
Last year, Trump threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, but this year, Trump lavishly praised Kim for his courage in approaching disarmament, but he still stressed that there is still work to be done and sanctions must be maintained until North Korea gives up its nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump said he has no time limit: "If it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter".
China and Russia have suggested that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the progress it has already made.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that "the Security Council's enforcement of sanctions must continue vigorously and unfailingly until we witness a complete, final and verified denuclearization".
The Security Council has unanimously stepped up sanctions against North Korea since 2006 with the aim of strengthening the financial channels for the production of ballistic and nuclear targets in Pyongyang.
