Harvard students complete a course on how to get enough rest
All undergraduate students at Harvard University are participating in a class this year designed to increase student rest, a counterpunch to the university's thriving macho culture of late-night weight-training on caffeine.
According to the researcher, students at the best university in the world are often quite ignorant of the basics of their own well-being.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of medicine at Harvard University who works in sleep research at Brigham and Women's Hospital, who designed the course, believes that it is the first of its kind in the United States.
Czeisler got the idea for the course after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
After the lecture, a young woman approached me and said: Why am I hearing about this only now, in my final year of study?
No one had ever told him about the need for sleep, which I think was surprising, he told the Telegraph in an interview.
The first-ever course this year will teach students how proper exercise habits support academic and athletic performance and improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor at Harvard Medical School and vice president of the university's health services, says that the university decided to hold the course after hearing of students suffering from severe sleep deprivation during the school week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
One section shows students a picture of a dorm room where they can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports equipment and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, the impact of sleep deprivation on sports performance and the importance of regular nighttime activities.
The second section tells participants how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus, complete with interactive icons, encourages participants to reflect on their daily routines.
We know that this has no direct impact on student behaviour.
However, we believe that they have a right to know about these issues, just as they have a right to know about the health effects of smoking", Professor Czeisler adds.
The all-night study marathons, according to Professor Czeisler, are still a source of pride, and modern technology and the ever-increasing pressures of students have made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
'Adequate and quality sleep should be the students' secret weapon against stress, fatigue and anxiety, and even against weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes a state in the brain that resembles starvation, which is why people are constantly hungry,' the professor points out.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old chemical and physical psychology student from California, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes during his first year at Harvard last year.
He says the course opened his eyes and gave him the impetus to organize a course that would cover all students on campus.
He hopes that all postgraduate students will be able to complete a similar course of study before moving to a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students set their alarm clocks to remind them of bedtime in addition to waking them up in the morning, and urges them to keep in mind the adverse effects of electronic monitors and LED lighting on circadian rhythms, which can make it difficult to fall asleep.
