German inventor of the Geiger counter
Next page in our Sunday Morning edition: September 30, 1882, Johannes Wilhelm Hans Geiger, the future physicist, was born in Germany on this day 136 years ago.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, which led to the development of the device later known as the Geiger counter.
The method became one of the pillars of science, and the meter became a central concept in pop culture. For example, the 1950 film "The Clocks of Coronado", in which Roy Rogers and Dale Evans portrayed scientists who looked like cowboys, is a good example:
Man: What the hell is that?
It's a geiger counter, and it's used to detect radioactive minerals, like uranium.
When you put the headphones on, you can actually hear the effect of radioactive radiation on the minerals.
Evans: "Look at that, it's really raining!"
Hans Geiger died in 1945 a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name lives on.
New cancer drug can teach the immune system to 'see' malignant cells
A new cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to 'see' and 'kill' malignant cells
The vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells as part of the treatment
The method involves isolating resistance cells from the patient and changing them in the laboratory
After treatment, the cells injected back into the body are able to "see" proteins typical of many cancers
The pilot vaccine has shown promising results in patients with various cancers.
For example, a patient with ovarian cancer had lost her cancer cells within 18 months of receiving a vaccine that teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells.
The method involves isolating resistant cells from the patient and modifying them in the laboratory so that they can absorb the HER2 proteins typical of many cancers.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, U.S.A., describes the method: "Our results show that this is a very promising vaccine".
HER2 "drives the growth of several types of cancer", explains Professor Berzofsky. "These include breast cancer, as well as cancers of the ovaries, lungs, and colon".
A similar approach - taking immune cells from a patient and teaching them to attack cancer cells - has also been successful in treating a type of leukemia.
