What is the Global Citizen Festival, and what has it done to reduce poverty?
The Global Citizen Festival, which takes place in New York City on Saturday, is a music event whose lineup is as impressive as its mission: to eradicate poverty from the world.
Now in its seventh year, the Global Citizen Festival draws tens of thousands of people to the lawns of New York's Central Park to hear performers such as Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to make known the event's true mission: to end extreme poverty by 2030.
Launched in 2012, the Global Citizen Festival is a continuation of the Global Powerty Project, an international advisory group that aims to eradicate poverty by increasing the number of people who take active action to eradicate poverty.
To get a free ticket to the event (if you are not willing to pay for a VIP ticket), the public has to perform various tasks or 'acts' such as volunteering, sending an email to a political decision-maker or making a phone call, or performing some other act that spreads awareness of the project's objectives.
But how has Global Citizen succeeded now that we only have 12 years to go?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert ticket a real way to get people to take action, or is it just one 'clicktivism' among others - the illusion that you can change the world by signing an e-mail address or sending a tweet?
Global Citizen reports that it has recorded over 19 million 'acts' for various purposes since 2011.
It says these actions have encouraged policy makers to announce commitments and principles worth over $37 billion, and spent in a way that will affect the lives of over 2.25 billion people by 2030.
As of early 2018, the group listed 390 commitments and declarations, from which more than $10 billion has already been spent or raised.
The group estimates that the funds so far have impacted the lives of nearly 649 million people worldwide.
The most important commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a UK-based group of investors and activists committed to 'helping children develop to their full potential', which pledged to provide $35 million to Rwanda to end malnutrition in the country, after receiving 4,700 tweets from activists as part of the Global Citizen campaign.
"Thanks to the British government, donors, governments of different countries and global citizens like you, we can put a history of social injustice and malnutrition in the newspapers", said Tracey Ullman, Power of Nutrition ambassador, to the audience at a concert in London in 2018.
The group also urged the UK Government to take action to improve nutrition for mothers and children by means of more than 5 000 actions, and announced funding for the Power on Nutrition project, which aims to tackle malnutrition by reaching 5 million mothers and children.
One of the frequently asked questions on the movement's website is: 'How do you think we can end extreme poverty?'
Global Citizen's answer: "The road ahead will be long and difficult, with many stumbling blocks.
But we will succeed, as the great civil rights and anti-apartheid movements before us did, because together we are stronger.
Deborra-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman will be headlining the movement's New York concert this year, and its star guard includes artists such as Janet Jackson, the Weeknd, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B and Janelle Monáe.
